 Part 1: Basic Commands to Control Services & Daemons (with simple explanation)

Linux uses systemd to manage services.
The command used is systemctl.

âœ” Start a service
sudo systemctl start httpd


Starts the service right now (Apache example).

âœ” Stop a service
sudo systemctl stop httpd


Stops the service immediately.

âœ” Restart a service
sudo systemctl restart httpd

###  Used when configuration changes are applied. ####

âœ” Reload service (without stopping)
sudo systemctl reload httpd


Reloads config without downtime (if service supports it).

âœ” Enable service on boot
sudo systemctl enable httpd


Service automatically starts after reboot.

âœ” Disable service
sudo systemctl disable httpd


Service wonâ€™t start after reboot.

âœ” Check service status
systemctl status httpd


Shows logs, active/inactive state, PID, etc.

âœ” View service logs (via journald)
journalctl -u httpd


View logs for a specific service.

âœ” View last 100 lines
journalctl -u httpd -n 100

âœ” Follow real-time logs
journalctl -u httpd -f

##::-->>> Part 2: Real-Time Company Scenarios + Commands <<<-----::##
ðŸ”¹ Scenario 1: Website is not loading

Check Apache/Nginx service:

systemctl status httpd


If inactive:

systemctl start httpd
systemctl enable httpd

ðŸ”¹ Scenario 2: Application service crashed unexpectedly

Check logs:

journalctl -u myapp.service -n 50


Restart:

systemctl restart myapp

ðŸ”¹ Scenario 3: Service fails on boot

Check enabled services:

systemctl is-enabled mysqld


Fix by enabling:

systemctl enable mysqld

ðŸ”¹ Scenario 4: Port is not listening

Check if service is running:

ss -tulnp | grep 80


If no output â†’ service not running â†’ restart service.

ðŸ”¹ Scenario 5: Configuration change not applied

Reload service:

systemctl reload nginx


If reload is not supported â†’ use restart.

ðŸ”¹ Scenario 6: High CPU usage from a service

Find the service:

top


Then restart:

systemctl restart tomcat


Check logs:

journalctl -u tomcat

##::-->>> Part 3: Common Issues & Solutions (with commands) <<<-----::##
â— Issue 1: Service fails to start

Check the reason:

systemctl status docker
journalctl -u docker -n 50


Fix missing directory or config, then restart:

systemctl restart docker

â— Issue 2: â€œUnit not foundâ€

Means service file is missing.

Check the directory:

ls /usr/lib/systemd/system/
ls /etc/systemd/system/


Reload daemon:

systemctl daemon-reload

â— Issue 3: Service stuck in failed state

Reset it:

systemctl reset-failed nginx
systemctl start nginx

â— Issue 4: Service not enabled after reboot

Fix:

systemctl enable crond

â— Issue 5: Permission denied

Check permissions:

ls -l /usr/bin/myapp
chmod +x /usr/bin/myapp


Restart:

systemctl restart myapp
